		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">of fear that the 32-bit support libraries will take several gigabytes and &quot;hav[ing] better use for that space&quot;.</div><br />This has to be the biggest oxymoron i've ever seen. No efficient program should take more than 4GB, ever, and as such, 64-bit software is completely commercial bloatware to make tech-wanabes buy it.<br /><br />Modern software is just written to waste RAM as if there's no tomorrow, and the whole transition to 64-bit thing is about that. A program running in 64-bit mode is going to compile into a program that uses much more RAM, because there's longer instructions, as all pointers and some variables will take more space.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
