	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">No efficient program should take more than 4GB, ever.</div><br />There are many applications that can benefit from large amounts of RAM.<br /><br />Sometimes you can use the extra RAM for working with large amounts of media data. There's simply no &quot;efficiency&quot; substitute for it in a lot of situtations. 3D modelling, video and audio editing, and games all can benefit hugely from the extra RAM.<br /><br />There are whole classes of algorithms, like <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dynamic_programming" class="postlink">dynamic programming</a> that allow order of magnitude efficiency speedups, but only if you have enough memory to match the size needs of the problem set. Memory vs speed tradeoffs. Compilers fall into this category, where better optimizations become practical with enough RAM.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


